INSERT INTO `#__content` VALUES ('1', '42', 'General Introduction', 'general-introduction', '', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Inclusion is the process of supporting persons with special needs: Disabilities, Difficulties and Disadvantages (DDD) (OECD, 2000, 2003) to enhance their wellbeing and development in different levels of societal settings (family, institution, workplace and community) (Bronfenbrenner, 1979, 1989). It enables them to cope in daily activities and consequently improves the quality of their life. Generally, inclusion is a broad and multidisciplinary field which is internationally well established but contextually contested. Consequently, every society the world over, given the existing challenges and means, has its approach to inclusive education services to promote the wellbeing and progress of its population with DDD. According to the Disabled Peoples’ International (DPI, 1981; BCODP, 1981), there is a distinction between the concepts: “impairment”-lacking part of or having defective body organ (e.g. amputated hand or hearing problem) which underlies dysfunctions in activities and “disablement” caused by unfavourable/inadequate societal structures (e.g. health, legal, educational, social….. services) that create barriers to wellbeing or effective participation in daily societal activities. Similarly, the World Health Organisation (WHO, 2002) frame of International Classification of Functioning Disability and Health (ICF) also distinguishes between “Personal Factors”- the defective structure(s) of human body organ(s) and “Environmental Factors”-the unfavourable organisation of societal structures that cause human limitation or restriction in daily activity participation. Since barriers arising from both impairment (personal factors) and disablement (environmental factors) as well as their negative interactions constitute determinants of societal exclusion, inclusion is defined as the process of replacing such barriers with facilitators to enhance the wellbeing, educational/economic empowerment and prosperity of the target population with DDD alongside their families, institutions, workplaces and communities that support them in daily activities. Thus, for cost-effectiveness and cost-efficiency purposes, the MUPUSUA inclusion initiative also envisages challenges of these key stakeholders who play significant roles in the life and development of the people with DDD.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Within our family and community settings, The MUPUSUA (2012) team pre-assessment results indicate that the prevalence of disabilities/disability related health condition is on the rise. Its origin, in conformity with findings of previous studies in other societies (Shonkoff &amp; Meisels, 2000), is traceable from a variety of sources: genetically inherited disorders; chemical imbalances in body system due to inadequate feeding and nutritional intake; neglected injuries sustained during ante-natal, peri-natal or post-natal stages in life; environmentally engineered sanitation challenges, psychosocially (psychologically/socially)-based health problems, among others. Because of lack of these disability/disability related diseases including HIV/AIDS awareness issues, community health promotion education and effective modes of prevention, treatment and management of such prevalence, many family/community members acculturated with superstitious beliefs often resort to inadequate traditionally-driven cultural modes of intervention. In addition to that, due to lack of conventional consultancy/practitioner expertise in inclusion/rehabilitation services in our society, persons with such prevalence often experience lifelong health condition and state of dependency, high rate of morbidity, low rate of life expectancy and high premature mortality rate. <br /></span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">In learning institution settings, most learners with DDD including: those with no access to schooling due to multiple factors; drop outs from schools; slow learners in schools;&nbsp; those struggling with education; those at risk of school exclusion due to academic/non-academic problems; those considered school failures and unemployed among others, all require special support to cope in learning or livelihood skills development activities. Besides these underachievers, there are also overachievers (talented and gifted learners) who require educational enrichment programme to enhance their development and academic excellence or high calibre professional orientation.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">In response to these societal categories of special needs support and human investment issues for poverty alleviation, a series of legal/policy frameworks have been promulgated and being implemented by the state of Cameroon and some private organisations to enhance inclusion/rehabilitation initiatives. Hitherto, many challenges are still evident in the area of specialist support provision. &nbsp;Hence, as contribution to efforts deployed by the state and other private organisations in response to these problems, MUPUSUA has emerged with modern scientific tools, strategies and expertise through a multitask force of health, social welfare, educational and economic support service providers to such persons with their families, institutions, work places and communities in order to facilitate their inclusion into the societal system.</span></p>\r\n<h2 class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">References</span></h2>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\">(British Council of Disabled People (BCODP,1981) The Social Model of Disability. <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Derby, UK. <br />Bronfenbrenner, U. (1979).The ecology of Human development: Experiment by<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; by Nature and Design. Thousand Oaks, CA: Sage.<br />Brofenbrenner, U. (1989). “Ecological System Theory”.&nbsp; In R. Vasta (Ed), Six &nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; theories of Development. Greenwich, CT: JAI Press.<br />Disabled Peoples’ International (DPI, 1981) The Social model of Disability.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; St John’s, Newfoundland: DPI.<br />Organisation of Economic Community and Development (OECD, 2000) UNESCO <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Classification of Special Needs Education Statistics and Indicators, Paris: OECD.<br />Organisation of Economic Community and Development (OECD, 2003) Students&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; with disabilities, difficulties and disadvantages, statistics and Indicators for &nbsp;<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Curriculum Access and Equity, Paris: OECD.<br />Shonkoff, J., P.&amp; Meisels, S., J. (2000). Handbook of Early Childhood Intervention.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. <br />WHO (2002) International Classification of Functioning, disability and health: <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; towards a common language for functioning, disability and health, Geneva.</span></p>', '', '0', '0', '0', '9', '2013-08-16 18:20:30', '496', '', '2013-08-24 00:39:59', '496', '0', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2013-08-16 18:20:30', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}', '{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}', '{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}', '4', '0', '6', '', '', '1', '1', '{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\"}', '0', '*', ''), ('3', '45', 'Who we are', 'who-we-are', '', '<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><br />MUPUSUA is a non-profit making, philanthropic, non-denominational and apolitical charity organisation whose objectives are oriented towards stakeholders’ awareness of and engagement in the process of inclusion of vulnerable persons. Our team of experts provide a range of multi-agency health, educational, social welfare and economic support services to people with Special Educational Needs (SEN): Disabilities (mental, physical and sensory), Difficulties (in learning, development and working life) and Disadvantages (in cultural, social, linguistic, socioeconomic and gender background) (SEN/DDD) alongside their families, organisations (institutions/workplaces) and communities in order to enhance their wellbeing, development and prosperity. We operate like a privately run community-based rehabilitation/inclusion organisation in cooperation with our local, national and international partners.</p>\r\n<h2 style=\"text-align: left;\">Our vision</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">To enhance individual/community wellbeing, sustainable development and prosperity</p>\r\n<h2 style=\"text-align: left;\">Our Motto</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Enabling access to wellbeing, development and prosperity</p>\r\n<hr class=\"system-pagebreak\" title=\"Our History\" />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span>Multipurpose Support Association (MUPUSUA) was created in January 2013 to support vulnerable persons (clients) with DDD and their communities (support service users) that enable them to cope in different aspects of daily life. The Association also strives to meet the special needs of its members, their relations and communities through a multi-agency taskforce and inter-professional services.</span></p>\r\n<hr class=\"system-pagebreak\" title=\"Objectives that guide our activities\" />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span>&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To provide support which help equalise learning and working opportunities for persons with Disabilities, Difficulties and Disadvantages (DDD);</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To promote the wellbeing, development and prosperity of families, organisations and communities that accommodate persons with DDD;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To sensitise communities on disability/disability-related diseases awareness including HIV/AIDS, prevention, treatment and management;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To engage fellow community members in the fight against DDD barriers through community health promotion outreach / individual psychosocial therapy;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To help fight against poverty of those with DDD and their communities through education and small scale economic empowerment support activities;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">To help support and protect children in their early years (age range 0-8) in general and those experiencing developmental difficulties in particular through early childhood intervention (ECI) initiative.</p>\r\n<hr class=\"system-pagebreak\" title=\"Budget\" />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The main source of funding for the organisation comes principally from membership contribution and partner support.</p>\r\n<h2 style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong><span>Annual Income Generation</span></strong><span>:</span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span>Membership registration;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span>Membership annual payments and support/ in-kind donation;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span>Fund raising activities and partner support</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span>At the beginning of every financial year, we come out with total annual expenses and vote a budget to run the organisation.</span></p>\r\n<h2 style=\"text-align: left;\"><span>Annual strategic planning and expenses</span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Payment of full/part time skilled/ semi-skilled staff of the organisation;<br />Financial incentive to disadvantaged background students and the unemployed working for the Association as volunteers;<br />Expenditure on material resources required for diverse support service projects;<br />Budget for the organisation’s permanent building construction works on a piece of land of 30 metres by 30 metres in Bolifamba, Mile 16, Buea;<br />Budget for staff training and expertise exchange trips nationally and internationally;<br />Annual volunteer trips, special annual events and missions;<br />Material/financial support given to learners assessed with SEN: disabilities/ difficulties/disadvantages/abilities (registered on the MUPUSUA system and provision scheme) or clients/ service users according to the choice of donors and supporting partners. This will exclude beneficiaries of state or other private support schemes. Terms and conditions apply and all financial expenses for this purpose are highly dependent on the available annual fund allocated by the Association as well as donors’/partners’ support.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Copies of the annual audition, accountability and transparency records, financial transactions and feedbacks are presented during membership meetings and sent by email or post to in-kind donors, partners and stakeholders to let them know how their supporting money is spent by our charity organisation.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<hr class=\"system-pagebreak\" title=\"Key Executive Staff\" />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><span><img style=\"float: left;\" alt=\"Dr. Ndame Thomas\" src=\"images/Dr._Ndame_Thomas.png\" height=\"320\" width=\"206\" /></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: large;\"><strong>Dr. Ndame Thomas</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: large;\">Founding Director/ General Manager </span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: large;\"><strong>Education:</strong> BA English/French University of Yaoundé I / MA in the Teaching of French University of Buea, Cameroon; MA Early Childhood Intervention (ECI), Malardalen University, Vasteras-Sweden; EdD (Doctor of Education) Special Educational Needs/ Inclusive Education, University of Exeter, UK. </span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: large;\"><strong>Professional experience:</strong></span><span><span style=\"font-size: large;\"> Bilingual (English/French) Education Secondary Instructor/ (Tertiary Level Lecturer), Special /Inclusive Education Researcher/Lecturer and Consultant/Practitioner with national/ international working experience in Cameroon, Sweden and the UK since 1994.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span></span></p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: large;\"><strong>Ms Nkoke Mirabel E.</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: large;\">Assistant Manager</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: large;\"><strong>Education:</strong> BA History and Curriculum Teaching, University of Buea-Cameroon;&nbsp; &nbsp;International MA in Social Work, Gothenburg University, Sweden; Diploma Course &nbsp;candidate in&nbsp; Psycho-medical Counselling, Centre for Natural Healing, Black ford, UK.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: large;\"><strong>Professional experience:</strong> Social work/ Social support with national/ international working experience in Cameroon, Sweden and the UK since 2000.</span></p>\r\n<p><br style=\"text-align: justify;\" /></p>', '', '1', '0', '0', '8', '2013-08-16 18:28:55', '496', '', '2013-09-02 04:33:39', '496', '0', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2013-08-16 18:28:55', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}', '{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}', '{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}', '14', '0', '7', '', '', '1', '149', '{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\"}', '0', '*', ''), ('7', '49', 'What we do', 'what-we-do', '', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">We constitute a multi-agency taskforce and inter-professional support service providers namely special/ inclusive educators, nurses, mental health practitioner paediatrician, health promotion expert, social worker, educational/clinical psychologists, psychosocial therapist, business consultant, nutritionist/Dietician, environmentalist, community engagement facilitator and human development ecologist. Beside the uni-/multi-disciplinary support, we cooperate with partner organisations and stakeholders to meet the special needs of our clients and service users.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">With the help of our local, national and international partners we intend to make a great difference in the life of those in need of special support and the various societal settings that support them in one way or the other. In this regard, we wish to establish partnership cooperation exchange in research and practice including resource support in any of the three major areas of support services envisaged by MUPUSUA. Support may be provided to individuals, groups, families, institutions or disadvantaged communities according to the desire and wish of the donors or supporting partner organisation. It may also be on monthly, quarterly, bi-annually and annually or an instant in-kind donation. Once the online resource support form is filled, we furnish you with more detailed information on the categories of individual(s), groups, families, communities or project(s) you intend to support. We are thankful and highly appreciate in advance whatever is available for the needy and vulnerable we support.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<hr class=\"system-pagebreak\" title=\"Key areas of support services\" />\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Inclusive Education is a multidisciplinary field that crosses and re-crosses many disciplinary and professional boundaries including those that enhance the state of well being (Health/ psychology/ Social Welfare), learning (Education/Human Rights) and employment (socio-economic condition)<strong>. </strong>Consequently,MUPUSUA targets these three major areas in response to diverse special needs identified in our community by a team of experts during the initial field pre-assessment exercise that underpin the creation of the organisation. The three project areas include: Alternative/Complementary Health Support/Care, Inclusive Education Services and Early Childhood Intervention. A detailed description including the code of practice, the constitution, policy (plan of action), the general organisation of resources/services and the workbook of internal rules/regulations of each of the areas of support services are found in the hard copy of our Handbook. Below is a summary description of each of the areas of support services delivered.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span>I-Alternative/Complementary health support/care </span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>-<strong>Community health promotion outreach</strong> based on the determinants of good health: food/nutrition; public/domestic environmental sanitation/hygiene; physical/ professional daily activities; general risk prevention/security issues;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>&nbsp;-<strong>Individual psychosocial therapy</strong> based on a range of psycho-medical health conditions (stress, anxiety, post traumatic disorders, phobia among others) /social wellbeing problems (care, support, accommodation, employment, bereavement, relationship in family/workplace, neglect, abuses, leisure/socialisation among others);</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span>II- Inclusive Education service </span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span>&nbsp; Individualised, grouped and</span></strong><span> <strong>Institutional support</strong>:</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>-Learning support (individualised/grouped) programmes for learners with diverse categories of disabilities, abilities and disadvantages in primary, secondary and tertiary education levels.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>-Enabling school placement/ rehabilitation for children with SEN/DDD abandoned in families and communities;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>-Supporting schools to implement the Disability Law No.83/013 and other related legal frameworks, to attain the national and UNESCO (1990, 1994) goals of Education for All (EFA)/inclusion and helping them to improve the quality of their educational services;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>&nbsp;-Consultancy and inclusive capacity building of local partner institutions accommodating our clients/service users with DDD;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>-Curriculum and teaching support to teachers of our local partner institutions;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span>Family and Community support</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>-Sensitising and engaging families/communities in disability/disability related disease awareness issues including HIV/AIDS prevention, treatment and management;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>&nbsp; </span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>-Economic empowerment through poverty alleviation strategies like: support for small scale businesses, livelihood skills training/development and sustainable development activities for the disabled, socioeconomically disadvantaged persons, families and communities. </span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span>III</span></strong><span>-<strong>Early Childhood Intervention (ECI) through the “First Good Step-FIGOST” Project </strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>This MUPUSUA inter-professional health, education and social welfare support initiative is designed to enhance positive development of children (age range 0-8 years) in different areas of life within and between family/school/community settings. It focuses on<strong>:&nbsp; </strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>-General support to save life; fight for rights to education and protecting children at risk of abuses (sexual, physical, psychological, moral) and child trafficking;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>-Special support to children experiencing diverse categories of developmental difficulties and their families.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span>Modes of</span></strong><span> <strong>Support service delivery</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>We use modern scientific tools which incorporate theoretical and practical approaches<strong>:</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span>Theoretical approach</span></strong><span>-theories, policies, laws and research including publication of articles /free download from the bi-annual monographs /compendia on our website;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span>Practical approach-</span></strong><span>screening/ identification/ assessment of special needs, counselling, consultancy, therapeutic intervention, volunteering in practical institutional/community works and education/training through lectures, workshops, seminars, videoconferencing and radio/TV programmes;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span>Referrals</span></strong><span> to other specialist services when and where necessary.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span>References</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 150%;\"><span>UNESCO (1990) The Jomtien Declaration of Education for All, Paris: UNESCO.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 150%;\"><span>UNESCO (1994) The Salamanca statement and Framework for Policy and Action</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 150%;\"><span>on Special Needs Education, Paris: UNESCO).</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 150%;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<hr class=\"system-pagebreak\" title=\"Modes of Support service delivery\" />\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 150%;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>As support service providers, we generally embark on a series of procedures. After consultation, screening and assessment of special needs of clients/service users and their registration on our provision scheme, practical support service or intervention is delivered by a professional or group of professionals in the area concerned. Our Special Educational Needs Coordinators (SENCOs)/Inclusive Education Managers manage the cooperation between professionals and the coordination of activities in the various family, institutional, workplace and community settings in which our clients/service users are supported. In this regard, we use modern scientific tools which incorporate theoretical and practical approaches to support service delivery.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span>Theoretical approach</span></strong><span>-theories, policies, laws and research including publication of articles /free download from the bi-annual monographs /compendia on our website;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span>Practical approach-</span></strong><span>screening/ identification/ assessment of special needs, counselling, consultancy, therapeutic intervention, volunteering in practical&nbsp; institutional/community works and education/training through lectures, workshops, seminars, videoconferencing and radio/TV programmes;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span>Referrals</span></strong><span> to other specialist services when and where necessary.</span></p>\r\n<h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>References</span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Ministry of Social Affairs (MINAS) (1983) The disability law No. 83/013 of July 21, <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1983. Yaoundé: MINAS, Cameroon.)<br />UNESCO (1990) The Jomtien Declaration of Education for All, Paris: UNESCO.<br />UNESCO (1994) The Salamanca statement and Framework for Policy and Action<br />on Special Needs Education, Paris: UNESCO.)&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<br />(UNESCO (2005) Guidelines for inclusion: Access to Education for All, Paris.</span></p>', '', '1', '0', '0', '15', '2013-08-16 18:32:25', '496', '', '2013-09-01 01:05:29', '496', '496', '2013-09-02 04:20:34', '2013-08-16 18:32:25', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}', '{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}', '{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}', '11', '0', '2', '', '', '1', '92', '{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\"}', '0', '*', ''), ('11', '54', 'Get Involved', 'get-involved', '', '<p style=\"text-align: left;\">If interested in any of our three key projects, you are welcome as a member. If willing to deliver skilled, semi-skilled and unskilled services through individual/group volunteering and family participation in institutional and community support services, you are welcome. Please, visit us or contact us by phone or email address indicated on our contact page.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span>Making a difference together </span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>With the help of our local, national and international partners we intend to make a great difference in the life of those in need of special support and the various societal settings that support them in one way or the other. In this regard, we wish to establish partnership cooperation exchange in research and practice including resource support in any of the three major areas of support services envisaged by MUPUSUA. Support may be provided to individuals, groups, families, institutions or disadvantaged communities according to the desire and wish of the donors or supporting partner organisation. It may also be on monthly, annually or an instant in-kind donation. Once the online resource support form is filled, we furnish you with more detailed information on the categories of individual(s), groups, families, communities or project(s) you intend to support. We are thankful and highly appreciate in advance whatever is available for the needy and vulnerable we support.</span></p>\r\n<h2 style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Types of support resources required by MUPUSUA:</strong></h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span>Human</span></strong><span>-researchers/practitioners/consultants/trainers for exchange of expertise and different levels of training opportunities for our personnel;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span>Materials</span></strong><span>-didactic materials like computers, science/language lab equipment, text books, stationery, assistive technology, white boards/screens, projectors, cars/vans for transportation of the vulnerable to/from various settings, playground equipment for kids, among others;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span>Financial</span></strong><span>-fund for: individual or group maintenance/tuition fees; development project(s) in school or schools; disadvantaged individual family or group of families, disadvantaged community project(s), general donation to any of the three MUPUSUA major support services or a specific sub support service.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a href=\"images/pdfs/MUPUSUA_support_form_opt.pdf\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><span style=\"font-size: 18pt;\"><img alt=\"pdf icon\" src=\"images/pdf_icon.png\" height=\"27\" width=\"26\" /></span></span><span style=\"font-size: 18pt;\"> </span><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><span style=\"font-size: 18pt;\">Click here to download our resource support form</span></span></a></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">(fill the form and send it as an attachment to <a href=\"mailto:info@mupusua.org\">info@mupusua.org</a>)<br data-mce-bogus=\"1\" /></span></p>', '', '1', '0', '0', '16', '2013-08-16 18:48:28', '496', '', '2013-09-09 08:02:12', '496', '0', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2013-08-16 18:48:28', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}', '{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}', '{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}', '14', '0', '2', '', '', '1', '86', '{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\"}', '0', '*', ''), ('12', '55', 'Partnering', 'partnering', '', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The types of partners we liaise with include:</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Local/national community members, authorities and organisations; medical establishments, learning institutions, social networks of NGOs/charity foundations and business organisations interested and willing to support us or share/ exchange expertise with us;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>International NGOs, charity foundations and organisations that are interested in any of our projects, willing to support us or cooperate with us through exchange of expertise in research/practical services.&nbsp;</span></p>', '', '1', '0', '0', '16', '2013-08-16 18:49:20', '496', '', '2013-08-24 01:19:12', '496', '0', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2013-08-16 18:49:20', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}', '{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}', '{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}', '3', '0', '3', '', '', '1', '11', '{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\"}', '0', '*', ''), ('15', '59', 'Volunteer with us', 'volunteer-with-us', '', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span>Information for partners intending to volunteer or study on internship/placement with us</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>Despite few challenges like in most developing countries, Cameroon is a peaceful and welcoming country to visit. The South West Region (English speaking zone) with capital in Buea in which is located the MUPUSUA headquarters has many attractive touristic sites ranging from: Mt Cameroon 4072 metres, the highest peak in West Africa; the nearby Debunscha west coast with the highest annual rainfall in Africa;&nbsp; abundant sunshine (Dry Season-October to May while Rainy Season June-September) to enjoy; dense equatorial forest with diverse fauna/flora; beautiful coastal beaches of the Atlantic Ocean with charming resorts; attractive botanical garden and zoological park. Besides that, the people are very welcoming and the cost of living is cheap. Its attractive and cheap hotels/motels also offer local, continental and international dishes to suit the needs/ taste of all customers. Buea also has a range of small and medium size super markets and country markets from which shopping is done. In addition, there are many local and traditional daily/weekly activities to make your stay in Buea interesting. If necessary detailed online information could be sent on the quality and price range of hotel services prior to any booking. But there is also the possibility of being lodged in student hostels or well catered accommodations during the Summer holidays. From the nearest international airport located in Douala, it takes merely 45 minutes’ drive to Buea. In any of the options, MUPUSUA will be making all the necessary arrangements including security guarantee to ensure that its visiting international partner representatives and volunteers have a safe and enjoyable trip in Cameroon.<br /></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><span>Individual or group volunteer internship/placement application</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span>An online form will be sent to applicant(s) after their expression of interest by email through a representative partner organisation.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span><a href=\"images/pdfs/mupusua_volunteer_form1.pdf\"><img alt=\"pdf icon\" src=\"images/pdf_icon.png\" height=\"37\" width=\"35\" /> <span style=\"font-size: large;\">Download our volunteer form</span></a><br /></span></p>', '', '1', '0', '0', '16', '2013-08-16 18:59:26', '496', '', '2013-09-09 08:05:23', '496', '0', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2013-08-16 18:59:26', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}', '{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}', '{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_naviga